Secrets of wine by Hernan Antolini

Overview

I am from Argentina. In the west region of my country, near the Andean mountains, red wine from France, has found a wonderfull place to growth. It seems that it is mostly related with the weather conditions (desert with differences in temperatures within the day and sunny) but, since red wine in Argentina is as famous as futbol or tango, everyone has an opinion on it. So, this dataset, i hope, will be a great opportunity to search for an educated opinion, mostly a scientific opinion, on this wonderfull beverage. As romans used to say : “In vino veritas” " ! (In wine, the truth)

This red wines data set consist of 13 variables and 1599 observations. There are very chemical related variables (free.sulfur.dioxide, fixed.acidity total.sulfur.dioxide, sulfates, chlorides, etc) what i will start ploting the common ones to explore the set. So my first quest is for “pH” because it use to be related with the kind of ground were the wine growth

OK, so it seems that pH is normaly distributed between our wines . lets check what is the distribution of quality -lets use factor to treat it as discrete. The wineQualityInfo.txt files inform us that pH describes “acidic” from very acidic (0) to very basic (14) and that most wines should be between 3 and 4

OK , its clear too. Another almost normal distribution so it is time to find out what makes those high quality wines being apart from that huge number of medium quality wines in terms of chemical variables.

The info file for our dataset has this information about acidicity : Most acids are nonvolatile (do not evaporate) -fixed acidity-, the rest is volatile, were high levels could lead to vinegar taste. So probably our outliers up the 3rd quartile (> 0.7) dont have good taste … Now check what about the distribution of dioxide variables

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 wines observed in this dataset with 12 variables which i would like to group in acid-related (fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid and pH), SO2-related (free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, and sulphates) , fermentation-related (alcohol, density and residual sugar) and quality and chlorides

Other observations 1. pH is normally distributed and should be around 3 and 4 2. quality goes from 0 to 10 with most observations around 5 and 6 as expected 3. acidity , fixed and volatile, affects taste. Citric acid also drive the “freshness” of wines so there are lot of work to do around acidity. 4. Prescence of SO2 affects the taste and nose of wine and we have some observations that need to be analyzed in details like those more than 500 with 50 ppm total sulfur dioxide. 5. Alcohol, residual sugar and density needs to be analyzed together.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

From my point of view the main features of this dataset is wine quality. Now the challenge is to understand how the grouped features (SO2 related, acidity related and fermentation related) affects wine perceived quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

As i mentioned above my plan is to find any correlations between SO2 vars, acidity vars and fermentation related vars between them and against quality

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

No at this time, just created variables from the dataset to analyze the distribution of alcohol

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

There are outliers or exceptional cases in some distributions theh need to be investigated further. Residual sugar and dioxide distributions are skewed with outliers that require further analysis.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

Red box focus on the area were high quality wines resides. The area goes from around 0.30 to 0.60 presence of citric acid and 0.2 to 0.4 volatile acidity. It looks like citric acid could be higher without affecting negatively the quality of wine. Citric acid gives a “fresh” sensation to wine taste.

Plot Two

Description Two

“Never in excess” …and we are not talking in this case about the alcohol level, we talk about free sulfur dioxide. There is a range of values were the prescense of free sulfure dioxide and the “bubbles” sensation goes hand in hand with wine quality ….but…if it is in excess then wine will be converted back to a normal wine.

Reflection

OK, reach the final of the exploration. It is a great dataset to learn and it is a very interesting topic mostly for countries like argentina where wine is so pervasive and most of argentinians like to have educated opinions on wine quality. I would like to have included in the dataset at least 1 additional variable: it would be nice to have the production year of the wine. The reasson is because it it perceived that older wines are better but not old wines got better the same. It suprised me the impact of acidity factors in wine quality. It would be nice to explore if there are any relation between acidity and different wineyards locations (that could be another variable to include in the dataset). Basically we could say that quality of wine is impacted by citric acid (direct) and volatile acidity (inverse). Additionaly , and closelly related with the fermentation process, as sugar get consumed to produce alcohol SO2 gets liberated and some gain prescense in the wine itself. A mid term prescense of SO2 with moderate to high alcohol graduation seems to inpact the quality of wine too. I got only minor problems during the analisis and they were not directly related with the dataset. It was in the bivariate section where sometimes it was difficult for me to express or review the relation with clarity using scatter plots and that’s the reasson why i choosed to move the plots to boxplots. I guess i needed to review in more detail the options to adjust scatter plots and better deal with different time of variables on them.
